<F P=101> General </F>
<H3> <TI>   `Desirable Signs' Seen on Nuclear Issue </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2712024393 Tokyo MAINICHI SHIMBUN in Japanese 26 Dec 93 
Morning Edition p 7 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW2712024393 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo MAINICHI SHIMBUN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By correspondent Hidetoshi Kaneko] </F>
  [Text] Beijing, 25 Dec -- Commenting on the issue of 
North Korea's refusal to permit international inspections of its 
nuclear sites, a high-ranking Chinese Foreign Ministry official 
said on 25 December, "desirable signs have already appeared." 
  The Chinese official's remarks strongly hinted that North 
Korea may be ready to accept international inspections. The 
official also disclosed that China is poised to cooperate with 
the new economic policy that North Korea has adopted. 
  China has publicly taken a neutral position on the North 
Korean nuclear issue. In fact, however, China is said to have 
urged North Korea to accept international inspections. The 
Chinese official was confident of progress in U.S.-North Korea 
dialogue, saying, "Compared with the situation six months ago, 
(U.S.-North Korea) dialogue is making steady headway." 
  He also said: "The Workers' Party of Korea recently held a 
plenary session of its Central Committee to adopt a very 
important policy of rebuilding North Korea and its economy. 
This policy is noteworthy." The official spoke highly of the 
"three-first policy North Korea has adopted to develop trade, 
agriculture and light industry." 
  The high-ranking Chinese official said: "I believe that 
China will continue to develop its normal, cooperative relations 
with North Korea based on the principle of equality and 
reciprocity." 
  His comments made it clear for the first time that China 
will 
cooperate with North Korea in rebuilding Pyongyang's economy. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

