<H3> <TI>   Sihanouk in Beijing; Condition Believed `Worsening' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2001130294 Tokyo MAINICHI SHIMBUN in Japanese 20 Jan 94 
Morning Edition p 6 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW2001130294 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo MAINICHI SHIMBUN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By correspondent Riichiro Amitani] </F>
  [Text] Beijing, 19 Jan -- Recently, Cambodian First Prime 
Minister Norodom Ranariddh and Second Prime Minister Hun Sen 
separately visited King Norodom Sihanouk at a hospital in 
Beijing. Diplomatic sources here think that King Sihanouk, who 
underwent an operation for cancer at the hospital, is now in 
serious condition. 
  Immediately after his rectum was operated on in October last 
year, King Sihanouk announced: "I have contracted cancer." He 
is currently being hospitalized at an army hospital in Beijing. 
Prime Minister Ranariddh reportedly visited the king at the 
hospital on the evening of 17 January, upon the delegation's 
arrival in Beijing. Prime Minister Hun Sen visited the king on 
18 January. The Sihanouk Office [name as published] and the 
Cambodian Embassy in Beijing have not given answers to why the 
two did not visit the king together. 
  Claiming that he is ill, King Sihanouk has been controlling 
Cambodian politics from Beijing. A diplomatic source said: 
"His health condition does not seem to be the same as it was 
when he initially chose to `pursue politics' from here. Despite 
the visits by the two prime ministers, no message has been 
delivered from the king. This indicates that his health 
condition is worsening." 

</TEXT>

