<F P=101> Military </F>
<H3> <TI>   Deng Planning To `Reshuffle Top Military Personnel' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1612063393 Tokyo SANKEI SHIMBUN in Japanese 15 Dec 93 
Morning Edition p 4 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW1612063393 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo SANKEI SHIMBUN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By Masaru Soma] </F>
  [Text] Hong Kong, 14 Dec -- A Western diplomatic source 
here disclosed on 14 December that Deng Xiaoping, China's most 
influential leader, left Beijing for Shanghai on 10 December. 
The source stated that during his stay in Shanghai, Deng will 
start working out plans to reshuffle top military personnel. 
The military leadership reshuffle was originally expected to 
take place in mid- December, but it has now become most likely 
that the reshuffle will take place after next February. 
  Every year, Deng spends the season of the year's end and the 
new year as well as the Lunar New Year (which falls on 10 
February) in Shanghai partly for the purpose of passing the 
winter. Citing as the basis for his observation that Deng has 
arrived in Shanghai, the same source points out that the Xijiao 
Guesthouse where Deng usually stays and its neighboring area 
have been put under stricter guard than usual. 
  Moreover, an informed source in Hong Kong states that 
"Deng's 
movements have become slower than before" but that "there are no 
problems with his health because his thinking is clear and he 
has a nimble mind." At the same time, the same source points 
out that because senior military leaders are accompanying him on 
his current visit to Shanghai, it can be expected that plans for 
the military leadership reshuffle are being worked out now. 

</TEXT>

